  "answer": "Ten works in the corpus specifically mention Greek or Roman antiquity:\n\n1. **cynewulf-elene-d2d132** (Elene, ch. 1) — The poem is set in the Roman era and explicitly refers to Constantine as 'the Caesar commanded, helm of the Romans,' 'lord of the Romans,' and 'king of the Romans.'\n\n2. **charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce** (Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I, chs 2, 4, 6, 7, 8, 11) — Mentions the Roman empire, Homer and 'the Greeks of Homer,' Aristotle, and Socrates.\n\n3. **charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03** (Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II, ch. 19) — Mentions Aristotle (Greek philosopher), Virgil and Horace (Roman poets).\n\n4. **charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2** (Traité de Législation: VOL I, chs 1, 2, 9, 10, 11, 15, 17, 19, 22) — Mentions 'ancient peoples of Greece and Rome,' Aristotle, Plato (Greek), Cicero (Roman), Roman law, Roman empire, Roman republic.\n\n5. **charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d** (Traité de Législation: VOL II, chs 2, 14) — Mentions 'ancient peoples of Italy and Greece' and Homer.\n\n6. **charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a** (Traité de Législation: VOL III, chs 30, 36, 37, 42, 48) — Mentions ancient Greece, 'republics of Greece,' Roman Republic, Roman empire, Roman conquests, Homer, Cicero, Virgil, Horace.\n\n7. **charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040** (Traité de Législation: VOL IV, chs 2–7, 13, 17, 23) — Mentions Roman empire, Roman Republic, Roman senators, Aristotle, Plato, Cicero, Caesar, Pompey, Homer, Virgil.\n\n8. **charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99** (Traité de la propriété: VOL I, chs 1, 7, 9, 12–20) — Mentions Roman law extensively, Aristotle, Plato, Cicero, Roman Republic, Roman empire under Augustus.\n\n9. **charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5** (Traité de la propriété: VOL II, chs 31, 44, 45, 47) — Mentions Roman empire, Aristotle, Virgil.\n\n10. **sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798** (Diwan-E-Zauq, ch. 15) — References 'Platos' (the Greek philosopher Plato) in a ghazal.\n\nAll other works in the corpus (Iqbal's Bang-E-Dara, Ghalib's Diwan, Cynewulf's Andreas and Juliana, Old English Elegies, Fichte's Denkfreiheit, and all Sanskrit/Kawi/Indic texts) did not surface specific mentions of Greek or Roman antiquity in English-body searches.",
